            i
            2
            π
            ξ
            x
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle e^{-i2\pi \xi x}}
   is to subtract 
  
    
      
        ξ
      
    
    {\displaystyle \xi }
   from every frequency component of function 
  
    
      
        f
        (
        x
        )
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle f(x).}
    So any sinusoidal component that was at 
  
    
      
        ξ
      
    
    {\displaystyle \xi }
   ends up at zero hertz, and the integral produces its amplitude, because (at least formally) all the other components are oscillatory and integrate to zero over an infinite interval.
The functions 
  
    
      
        f
      
    
    {\displaystyle f}
   and 
  
    
      
        
          
            
